                     <interp inst="t18300415-246-person2145" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I purchased a table of the prosecutor, and he was to send the balance of a 10l. note - I gave the note to the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-246-person2146">
                  BENJAMIN 
                  JOSEPH
               <interp inst="t18300415-246-person2146" type="surname" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-246-person2146" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-246-person2146" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . He never returned, and I thought some accident might have happened to him; I went to Mr. Clark's, at Maida-hill, who showed me the receipt - I went with his mother to a lodging, which he had taken that day in St. Giles'; we waited till half-past one o'clock in the morning when he came home - his mother questioned him how he could do as he had done; he gave up the balance, 5l. 2s. 6d., which he had, and acknowledged he had bought some books, and bought a man, in his company, a new coat - he said he had spent 3l. odd, and the rest he could not give any account of; he had behaved very well till this time, and I did not wish to prosecute him had it not been on account of his obstinacy - I should think he could get employ again; he was a little in liquor- I cannot say he was drunk.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 18.</p>
